<subSubSection box="[199,1383,680,707]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,356,1535]" box="[199,1383,680,707]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,680,706]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Large, smooth carapace with an outline that makes a sharp angle at the posteroventral margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="542" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,356,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,716,742]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Description.</emphasis>
Carapace slightly concave in the central-ventral margin. Dorsal margin angular in the antero and posterodorsal portions in adults, while in juveniles the anterior angular portion promotes a strong fall to the anterior margin. In juveniles the posterodorsal cardinal angle is lower. Anterior margin rounded in both stages, unlike the posterior margin in adults, which is more rectangular, and in juveniles it is triangular. Maximum length at the ventral region. Maximum height at anterodorsal region, coinciding with the location of the cardinal angle. LV larger than RV with evident overlap along the central ventral margin, in juvenile specimens there is overlap along the dorsal margin, making the cardinal angle more prominent. In dorsal view, the greatest width is at the posterior margin, but narrower in the juvenile form. Smooth outer surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,356,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,358,1004,1030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Observations</emphasis>
. A very large and elongated species compared to the others of the genus. This species stands out for its size. First, it was considered that this species is of the marine genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Brady, Crosskey &amp; Robertson, 1867" authorityName="Brady, Crosskey &amp; Robertson" authorityYear="1867" class="Ostracoda" family="Krithidae" genus="Krithe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1009,1081,1040,1066]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Krithe</emphasis>
Brady, Crosskey &amp; Robertson, 1867
</taxonomicName>
, but this genus is typical of deep waters, and so this idea was discarded. Detailed comparisons were also made with the species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anderson" authorityYear="1966" box="[363,487,1112,1138]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cyprididae" genus="Damonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[363,487,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Damonella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described and deposited by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tome, M. E. T. R. &amp; Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L." box="[799,1004,1112,1139]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" pagination="153 - 176" refId="ref17084" refString="Tome, M. E. T. R., Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L. (2014) Taxonomic studies of non-marine ostracods in the Lower Cretaceous (Aptian-lower Albian) of post-rift sequence from Jatoba and Araripe basins (Northeast Brazil): Stratigraphic implications. Cretaceous Research, 48, 153 - 176. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2013.12.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Tome 
<emphasis box="[868,923,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Araripe, R. &amp; Oliveira, D. &amp; Tome, M. E. &amp; Mello, R. M. &amp; Barreto, A. M. F." box="[1054,1281,1112,1139]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" pagination="104766" refId="ref12613" refString="Araripe, R., Oliveira, D., Tome, M. E., Mello, R. M. &amp; Barreto, A. M. F. (2021) Foraminifera and Ostracoda from the lower Cretaceous (Aptian - lower Albian) Romualdo formation, Araripe Basin, northeast Brazil: Paleoenvironmental inferences. Cretaceous Research, 122, 104766. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2021.104766" type="journal article" year="2021">
Araripe 
<emphasis box="[1145,1200,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
(2021)
</bibRefCitation>
in the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Ivan de Medeiros Tinoco Microfossils Collection</emphasis>
. The studied form is very large when compared to 
<taxonomicName authority="Tome et al., 2014" authorityName="Tome" authorityYear="2014" class="Ostracoda" family="Cyprididae" genus="Damonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandiensis">
<emphasis box="[1174,1437,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Damonella grandiensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Tome, M. E. T. R. &amp; Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L." box="[151,347,1184,1211]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" pagination="153 - 176" refId="ref17084" refString="Tome, M. E. T. R., Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L. (2014) Taxonomic studies of non-marine ostracods in the Lower Cretaceous (Aptian-lower Albian) of post-rift sequence from Jatoba and Araripe basins (Northeast Brazil): Stratigraphic implications. Cretaceous Research, 48, 153 - 176. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2013.12.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Tomé 
<emphasis box="[221,278,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
, 2014
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Tome et al., 2014" authorityName="Tome" authorityYear="2014" box="[402,811,1184,1211]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cyprididae" genus="Damonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ultima">
<emphasis box="[402,605,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Damonella ultima</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Tome, M. E. T. R. &amp; Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L." box="[611,811,1184,1211]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" pagination="153 - 176" refId="ref17084" refString="Tome, M. E. T. R., Lima Filho, M. F. &amp; Neumann, V. H. M. L. (2014) Taxonomic studies of non-marine ostracods in the Lower Cretaceous (Aptian-lower Albian) of post-rift sequence from Jatoba and Araripe basins (Northeast Brazil): Stratigraphic implications. Cretaceous Research, 48, 153 - 176. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2013.12.007" type="journal article" year="2014">
Tomé 
<emphasis box="[681,738,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
, 2014
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. When compared, it presents the same characteristics of the species found by 
<bibRefCitation author="Araripe, R. &amp; Oliveira, D. &amp; Tome, M. E. &amp; Mello, R. M. &amp; Barreto, A. M. F." box="[386,620,1220,1247]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" pagination="104766" refId="ref12613" refString="Araripe, R., Oliveira, D., Tome, M. E., Mello, R. M. &amp; Barreto, A. M. F. (2021) Foraminifera and Ostracoda from the lower Cretaceous (Aptian - lower Albian) Romualdo formation, Araripe Basin, northeast Brazil: Paleoenvironmental inferences. Cretaceous Research, 122, 104766. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. cretres. 2021.104766" type="journal article" year="2021">
Araripe 
<emphasis box="[479,536,1220,1246]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">et al.</emphasis>
(2021)
</bibRefCitation>
. It is worth noting that they are totally smooth specimens with a difficult level of identification, since they do not have ornamentation to use for comparisons. In the present study, we chose to call 
<typeStatus box="[229,327,1292,1318]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">holotype</typeStatus>
Nº. DGEO-CTG-UFPE-1511 as an adult form and the 
<typeStatus box="[951,1047,1293,1319]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">paratype</typeStatus>
Nº. DGEO-CTG-UFPE-1512 as a young form, however further studies with a larger population would be necessary to recognise the male carapace and others ontogenetic stages.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,356,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,592,1400,1427]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Occurrence and associated fauna</emphasis>
. It was recorded in the Santo Antônio section, at the following depths (from base to top): 1.8; 2.1; 2.25; 3.1; 3.4; 3.45; 3.55; 3.65; 3.85 and 
<quantity box="[850,931,1436,1463]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.05" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" unit="m" value="4.05">4.05 m</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Tomé &amp; Araripe &amp; Oliveira &amp; Barreto &amp; Prado &amp; Pedrosa &amp; Pereira &amp; Nascimento &amp; Ng, 2022" authorityName="Tomé &amp; Araripe &amp; Oliveira &amp; Barreto &amp; Prado &amp; Pedrosa &amp; Pereira &amp; Nascimento &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2022" box="[941,1240,1436,1462]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cyprididae" genus="Mongolianella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aptianensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[941,1240,1436,1462]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Mongolianella aptianensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1247,1336,1437,1463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1247,1336,1437,1463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
does not occur in association with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Poag" authorityYear="1962" box="[437,573,1473,1498]" class="Ostracoda" family="Cuneocytheridae" genus="Dicrorygma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Podocopida" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[437,573,1473,1498]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Dicrorygma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Christensen" authorityYear="1965" box="[589,727,1472,1498]" class="Ostracoda" genus="Orthorygma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="7" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[589,727,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Orthorygma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
?) 
<emphasis box="[757,866,1472,1498]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">dimorpha</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,356,1535]" box="[199,1181,1508,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,508,1508,1534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Stratigraphic distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[522,593,1508,1534]" name="Brazil" pageId="7" pageNumber="542">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, Araripe Basin, Romualdo Formation, upper Aptian.
</paragraph>
